{
  "texts": [
    "By unifying tool invocations under one agent, it becomes possible to effectively learn the interconnectedness between tools, thereby compensating for potential information gaps arising from using tool-specific agents.",
    "Note the difference from Li et al. (2024), here we are discussing the granularity of division-of-labor among agents with different responsibilities, rather than the voting quantity among mutually equal agents.",
    "Human Evaluation.",
    "To get a deeper understanding of the quality of trajectories generated by different methods, we manually compare them from the number of planning rounds, the logical correctness of thoughts, action types, action parameters, and overall coherence.",
    "The detailed human evaluation process can be found in Appx."
  ]
}